      <hedline>
        <hl1>Into the Medicare Mix</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr James A Slater letter, commenting on Sept 12 article, offers some suggestions on ways of fixing Medicare</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Experts See Fix for Medicare as One Tough Proposition'' (front page, Sept. 12):</p>
        <p>Rather than having to choose between the politically contrasting solutions of either governmental (bureaucratic but essentially beneficent) or private (profiteering but essentially efficient), another choice would be a therapeutic dose of realism.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Experts See Fix for Medicare as One Tough Proposition'' (front page, Sept. 12):</p>
        <p>Rather than having to choose between the politically contrasting solutions of either governmental (bureaucratic but essentially beneficent) or private (profiteering but essentially efficient), another choice would be a therapeutic dose of realism.</p>
        <p>First, we must recognize that one plan will not fit all segments of society, yet we must remember that all segments of our society are ultimately interconnected. Second, some people can afford to pay more for health care than others, and should, since an expensive, world-class, technology-driven health care system cannot be free or cheap for everyone. And third, the quality of care, the morale and the dedication of nurses, doctors and researchers cannot be diminished.</p>
        <p>JAMES A. SLATER, M.D.  New Canaan, Conn., Sept. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
